<DOC><DOCNO> AP890227-0212 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2302EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0724 02-27 0321</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,0326</SECOND><HEAD>Seven Rebels, Three Soldiers Die in Peruvian Ambush</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with seven rebels killed, other details.No pickup</HEAD><DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three soldiers and seven Maoist guerrillaswere killed when rebels ambushed an army truck on a mountain roadnear this state capital, officials said Monday.   Five soldiers and ``numerous'' rebels were wounded in thefighting Sunday at an isolated spot in Peru's southern highlands, amilitary communique said.   Elsewhere, authorities said security forces fatally shot fivesuspected members of the Shining Path guerrilla group on Monday whenthey burst into a house on the outskirts of Huancayo, a major cityin the central Andes 140 miles east of Lima.   Civilian court officials said about 20 police and soldierswearing hoods barged in after receiving information guerrillas wereusing it as a safe house.   The local district attorney's office said it was not clear if thefive young men were armed. Police and the military refused toprovide information on the shooting.   In other violence, police said Shining Path rebels on Mondaykilled the mayor of Mantaro, a district 20 miles north of Huancayo.They said two men and a woman shot Teodoro Tovar, a member of thegoverning center-left Aprista Party.   A military communique issued in Ayacucho said the guerrillaambush of the army truck occurred shortly before nightfall Sunday 20miles northeast of Ayacucho. The provincial capital lies 235 milessouthest of Lima.   The report said a truck carrying 15 soldiers to the nearby armypost of Julcamarca was caught in a cross fire by about 50 rebelspositioned on slopes above the road.   The wounded were evacuated to Ayacucho, an old colonial town thatwas the birthplace of the Shining Path insurgency nine years ago.   Since 1980, more than 12,000 people have died in Peru's politicalviolence and the Shining Path has expanded its insurgency throughoutthis impoverished country.</TEXT></DOC>